  <p>According to an study conducted by the Construction Sector’s Economic Research Centre (<em>Centro de Estudios Económicos del
    Sector de la Construcción</em> – CEESCO), the key trends in the construction industry at the end of March 2019 are marked by
    the decrease in average prices of inputs, derived from the downturn in construction sector activity, that normally occurs
    at the beginning of a new presidential term. The sector dynamism is expected to pick up over the coming months with the
    beginning of several infrastructure projects and programs promoted by the federal government.</p>

  <p>During the beginning of the year, the highly dynamic origination of mortgage loans from National Housing Institutes
    more than offset the low budget of subsidies exercised in this period. Additionally, the titling of homes is expected to
    gain further momentum during 2Q19, as the Mexican Federal Institute for Workers’ Housing (<em>Instituto del Fondo Nacional
    de la Vivienda para los Trabajadores</em> – “INFONAVIT”) announced  the launch of a new program aimed at increasing the credit
    limit granted to its low-income affiliates, which will surely bolster sector activity.</p>


